courses.learning_outcomes:
It is expected that by the end of this course students will be able to:

• identify common features of academic texts;
• identify an appropriate topic and conduct research for an academic essay;
• select and organise relevant information into a structured, coherent text;
• avoid acts of academic dishonesty by documenting, quoting, paraphrasing, summarising and synthesising sources appropriately;
• formulate an academic argument with logical reasoning and supporting evidence;
• critically evaluate claims and corresponding evidence;
• adopt a process writing approach;
• deliver presentations purposefully, effectively and confidently; and
• review and reflect on their own language learning.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. understand and identify common features of academic writing and speaking;
2. identify common academic text structures and apply this knowledge to enhance comprehension and analytical skills;
3. conduct topic, purpose and audience analyses when writing academic texts;
4. conduct research to read widely and critically, and evaluate digital source materials to assess their credibility;
5. paraphrase, summarize, synthesize, and quote reading material appropriately and purposefully, using APA style;
6. organize ideas into a cohesive and coherent text, employing logical reasoning and analysis to strengthen the connections between ideas;
7. engage in peer review to evaluate others’ work;
8. deliver oral presentations and engage effectively and confidently with questions (as both presenter and audience member) and with the audience; anddeliver oral presentations effectively and confidently to small groups (or online if circumstances dictate); and
9. utilize online language resources to facilitate self-directed language learning.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. Identify premises (including unstated assumptions) and conclusions of inductive arguments;
2. Represent the flow of an argument through standardization and diagramming;
3. Analyse the use of persuasive techniques in English language spoken, written and multimedia texts;
4. Evaluate the acceptability, relevance and strengths of arguments; and,
5. Apply effective source-use skills.

By the end of this course, students will:

1. Understand the purpose, function, structure, and language of reflective writing and informative writing;
2. Produce the above-mentioned text types;
3. Understand content-related and subject-specific language and vocabulary; and
4. Use them appropriately both within and outside of performing arts.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. Analyze a literary text using different critical theories;
2. Compose an original, logical and well-reasoned academic paper in the form of a literary analysis essay;
3. Deliver an analytical presentation/discussion based on their literary analysis essay; and
4. Undertake in-depth analysis and evaluation/critique of their own written work and the work of their classmates.

Upon completion of this course, you will be able to:

1. demonstrate confidence in impromptu speaking;
2. write a professional email using the appropriate tone, style, vocabulary and content;
3. create a presentation outline; and
4. present ideas convincingly to a professional audience in a group oral presentation.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Employ common persuasion techniques, language, and rhetorical structures to formulate and present spoken and written arguments during discussion, presentation and essay writing;
2. Understand and practice discussion skills and language in an academic setting;
3. Summarize, paraphrase and synthesize reading material from original sources to support a thesis;
4. Demonstrate the correct use of vocabulary, sentence structure, grammar, and APA format in writing a formal essay;
5. Deliver a well-organized persuasive academic presentation to classmates and teachers to share meaningful research findings; and
6. Field a question-and-answer session following a presentation.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. write a research proposal;
2. conduct literature search and write literature reviews;
3. describe research methodology and results;
4. write a discussion section of a research paper;
5. write an abstract; and
6. give an academic presentation.

courses.course_syllabus:
Learning topics include:

1. writing research proposals;
2. conducting and writing literature reviews;
3. writing different sections of an experimental research paper: methodology, results, and discussion;
4. writing abstracts; and
5. academic presentation skills.

courses.learning_outcomes:
In general, through the course students will learn to:

1. understand the structure and style of academic texts;
2. demonstrate academic writing skills focusing on specific academic genres; and
3. give well-researched persuasive presentations effectively using appropriate organizational patterns.

More specifically, by the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

a) read an academic research article and identify key components including the research question, hypotheses, methodology, findings and conclusion;
b) summarize an academic research paper both verbally and in writing;
c) respond critically to a research paper by spelling out clear criteria of evaluation and support review content with evidence and examples;
d) recognize and demonstrate language features in the academic register;
e) research for quality input and organize such input to form a logical, coherent persuasive presentation using apt organizational patterns;
f) demonstrate verbal and non-verbal delivery skills when giving presentations; and
g) support presentations with visuals in a skillful manner.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. understand the structure and style of architectural documents;
2. demonstrate architectural literacy with a focus on specific genres;
3. construct structured prompts to generate original conceptual visualizations
4. communicate ideas that are well-structured and convincing in writing; and
5. express ideas and views clearly in prepared and impromptu speeches.

courses.course_syllabus:
Learning topics include:

1. descriptive writing and prompt literacy skills for architectural studies;
2. components and important moves in critical response and proposal writing;
3. critical, analytical, and persuasive writing skills for effective communication in architecture; and
4. presentation and impromptu speaking skills for critical evaluation.

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. make critical judgments about information sources;
2. implement reading strategies to select and understand news articles;
3. identify implement reading strategies to select and understand news articles;
4. write a documented summary report exploring multiple sides of an issue;
5. create proper in-text citations & reference list using APA 7th;
6. write a one paragraph article summarizing the authors main ideas;
7. ethically utilize AI Chatbots to help critically assess articles and improve their writing;
8. give informative presentations on current issues relating to business, science, and technology using appropriate language and structure;
9. develop their presentation delivery & visual aid skills;
10. give a self-evaluation on their presentations; and
11. evaluate and provide constructive feedback on peer presentations.

courses.course_syllabus:
Learning topics include:

1. reading strategies;
2. critical analysis and synthesis of information sources with the assistance of AI;
3. summary and writing skills;
4. general presentation skills;
5. self-evaluation & peer assessment techniques; and
6. leveraging AI to enhance students' understanding of English language usage.

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will have:

1. Further developed their academic and general writing skills for health sciences and healthcare contexts;
2. Strengthened their research, citation, and referencing skills;
3. Given effective seminar presentations for academic and general purposes; and
4. Demonstrated a proficient use of specialist vocabulary in Health Sciences and Healthcare.

Course Objectives

To enhance students’ listening and speaking competence by:

1. appreciating and attending to some essential features of the listening process;
2. appreciating and attending to some essential features of spoken English;
3. identifying and employing appropriate strategies for effective communication;
4. engaging in simulated/authentic language learning/language use situations; and
5. evaluating for themselves their listening and speaking processes.

Performance Objectives

By the end of the course, students should be able to listen and respond effectively by:

1. processing linguistic forms;
2. identifying the intention of the speaker(s);
3. understanding the whole message rather than individual utterances;
4. interpreting and evaluating the message conveyed; and
5. responding appropriately in various settings.

By the end of this course, students will have further developed their skills in:

1. understanding the purpose of academic writing;
2. establishing a valid research/essay topic;
3. understanding the important stages of the writing process;
4. paraphrasing and summarizing the reading material;
5. blending quotes and paraphrases into the text;
6. organizing a cohesive and coherent text;
7. employing vocabulary and sentence structures at an appropriate level of formality;
8. using the APA format to document sources properly; and
9. engaging in self-initiated independent language learning through online resources.

Upon completion of the course, you will be able to:

1. develop intercultural communication competence;
2. demonstrate the ability to present information clearly and concisely;
3. analyze and discuss business cases, and orally justify and defend your work, using effective verbal and non-verbal communication strategies, and;
4. write analytical reports collaboratively, comparing and contrasting information, while using appropriate structure and language.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. Evaluate the objective reliability of sources;
2. Synthesize multiple sources of information to write concise summaries and reports;
3. Appreciate diverse approaches to traditional medicine across the globe;
4. Understand and discuss socio-political factors related to traditional medicine;
5. Actively engage in discussion and express their views on topics covered in the course;
6. Apply a range of reading strategies to cope with reading longer, complex texts; and
7. Utilize a range of medical terminology.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. conceptualize a “design argument";
2. analyze architectural precedents;
3. verbalize architectural designs; and
4. present a design in a formal and persuasive manner.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. identify, deconstruct and organise key components of a research proposal;
2. identify and apply rhetorical strategies in written and spoken academic texts;
3. edit academic texts for coherence, clarity and accuracy; and
4. apply oral presentation skills in scholarly contexts.

courses.course_syllabus:
Learning topics include:

1. understanding the research writing process;
2. writing the introduction, literature review and methodology sections of a research report and proposal;
3. textual analysis of research reports and journal articles;
4. academic editing; and
5. giving oral research presentations.

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. apply principles of good writing to plan and revise professional documents;
2. write project proposals and project reports effectively using the conventions of standard written English;
3. give a short oral presentation on a project proposal;
4. express ideas with a range of formal vocabulary and grammatical structures; and
5. utilize online resources for independent English learning.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• understand the academic writing conventions in their discipline;
• identify the components of a research paper;
• synthesize sources and write an analytical literature review;
• describe and discuss findings effectively; and
• write a concise and coherent research proposal.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. Analyze the basic structure of an essay and use that analysis to structure their own writing;
2. Compose original, logical and well-reasoned essays by demonstrating their awareness of the issues involved, by distinguishing between opinion and fact, by recognizing opposing points of view and underlying assumptions, by using supporting evidence and by choosing and applying a variety of writing strategies;
3. Undertake in-depth analysis and evaluation/criticism of their own written work and the work of other students in the class;
4. Deliver an analytical discussion of an academic essay; and
5. Demonstrate university-level competence in grammar and syntax.

By the end of this course, students will have:

1. Improved their critical reading skills through a survey of numerous food-related texts;
2. Written descriptive and reflective texts and comprehensive summaries;
3. Expanded their English language proficiency through the use of media technologies;
4. Collaborated with peers to create and produce their own video programme;
5. Conducted audience and purpose analyses for summaries and video presentations;
6. Enhanced their English-speaking skills through in-class discussions of food-related topics;
7. Continued to develop their research skills; and
8. Engaged in self-directed learning.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. analyse the language and rhetoric of sample speeches, so as to appreciate the content and delivery employed by the speakers;
2. understand the importance of rhetoric in speeches;
3. apply Cicero’s five rhetorical stages: invention, disposition, style, memory and delivery; and
4. write and deliver formal and informal speeches effectively.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. demonstrate a critical understanding of what meaningful intercultural communication entails;
2. demonstrate the ability to recognize and appreciate cultural and linguistic diversity;
3. make reasoned verbal and non-verbal choices in intercultural encounters;
4. produce coherent, insightful accounts of their intercultural experience in English; and
5. reflect on and assess their L2/ cultural self-awareness and intercultural communication skills, and set realistic goals for further enhancement of their English language proficiency, intercultural competence, and global-mindedness.
